    "source_sections": {
      "references": "[Ba29] H. Balakran, On the values of $n$ which make $(2n)!/(n+1)!(n+1)!$ an integer. J. Indian Math. Soc. (1929), 97-100.\n \n [EGRS75] Erd\\H{o}s, P. and Graham, R. L. and Ruzsa, I. Z. and Straus, E. G., On the prime factors of $(\\sp{2n}\\sb{n})$. Math. Comp. (1975), 83-92.\n \n [Er68c] P. Erd\\H{o}s, Aufgabe 557. Elemente Math. (1968), 111-113.",
      "remarks": "A conjecture of Erd\\H{o}s, Graham, Ruzsa, and Straus \\cite{EGRS75}. It is open even for $k=2$.\n\nBalakran \\cite{Ba29} proved this holds for $k=1$ - that is, $(n+1)^2\\mid \\binom{2n}{n}$ for infinitely many $n$. It is a classical fact that $(n+1)\\mid \\binom{2n}{n}$ for all $n$ (see Catalan numbers). \n\nErd\\H{o}s, Graham, Ruzsa, and Straus observe that the method of Balakran can be further used to prove that there are infinitely many $n$ such that\\[(n+k)!(n+1)! \\mid (2n)!\\](in fact this holds whenever $k<c \\log n$ for some small constant $c>0$). \n\nErd\\H{o}s \\cite{Er68c} proved that if $a!b!\\mid n!$ then $a+b\\leq n+O(\\log n)$."
    },
    "source_state": "open",
    "tags": [
      "number theory",
      "factorials"
    ]
  },
